[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":475},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F02\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F02\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F02\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F02\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack\u002F":450,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F02\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack\u002F":459},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200502\u002F2917226562\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":433,"date":434,"description":435,"extension":436,"lang":437,"meta":438,"navigation":111,"path":439,"readingMinutes":440,"seo":441,"standalone":442,"stem":443,"tags":444,"tldr":447,"updated":434,"url":448,"__hash__":449},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-04-execution-context-call-stack.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (4): Execution Context and the Call Stack","1000586009",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":427},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,31,34,37,126,136,190,197,208,212,218,221,317,341,344,350,365,371,374,380,386,389,407,411,423],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"If you don't have a solid grasp of execution context and the call stack, things get pretty confusing once you start building real stuff. So let's get it sorted out.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"execution-context","Execution Context",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":29,"src":30},"Execution context","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-02%2016.21.33.png",[17,32,33],{},"In JavaScript, every function has \"its own execution context.\" This is a really important point.",[17,35,36],{},"For example, you can't just reach past a function and call another one inside it:",[38,39,44],"pre",{"className":40,"code":41,"language":42,"meta":43,"style":43},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function sayHi() {\n  function sayName() {\n    console.log('Ray');\n  }\n}\n\nsayName(); \u002F\u002F sayName is not defined;\n","js","",[45,46,47,64,75,94,100,106,113],"code",{"__ignoreMap":43},[48,49,52,56,60],"span",{"class":50,"line":51},"line",1,[48,53,55],{"class":54},"sWyjQ","function",[48,57,59],{"class":58},"sj_SG"," sayHi",[48,61,63],{"class":62},"sMAXC","() {\n",[48,65,67,70,73],{"class":50,"line":66},2,[48,68,69],{"class":54},"  function",[48,71,72],{"class":58}," sayName",[48,74,63],{"class":62},[48,76,78,81,84,87,91],{"class":50,"line":77},3,[48,79,80],{"class":62},"    console.",[48,82,83],{"class":58},"log",[48,85,86],{"class":62},"(",[48,88,90],{"class":89},"sTRMh","'Ray'",[48,92,93],{"class":62},");\n",[48,95,97],{"class":50,"line":96},4,[48,98,99],{"class":62},"  }\n",[48,101,103],{"class":50,"line":102},5,[48,104,105],{"class":62},"}\n",[48,107,109],{"class":50,"line":108},6,[48,110,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},true,"\n",[48,114,116,119,122],{"class":50,"line":115},7,[48,117,118],{"class":58},"sayName",[48,120,121],{"class":62},"(); ",[48,123,125],{"class":124},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F sayName is not defined;\n",[17,127,128,129,131,132,135],{},"So ",[45,130,118],{}," is trapped inside ",[45,133,134],{},"sayHi",". The same goes for variables — even after you've run the function:",[38,137,139],{"className":40,"code":138,"language":42,"meta":43,"style":43},"function sayHi() {\n  var name = 'Ray';\n}\nsayHi();\nconsole.log(name); \u002F\u002F name is not defined;\n",[45,140,141,149,166,170,177],{"__ignoreMap":43},[48,142,143,145,147],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,144,55],{"class":54},[48,146,59],{"class":58},[48,148,63],{"class":62},[48,150,151,154,157,160,163],{"class":50,"line":66},[48,152,153],{"class":54},"  var",[48,155,156],{"class":62}," name ",[48,158,159],{"class":54},"=",[48,161,162],{"class":89}," 'Ray'",[48,164,165],{"class":62},";\n",[48,167,168],{"class":50,"line":77},[48,169,105],{"class":62},[48,171,172,174],{"class":50,"line":96},[48,173,134],{"class":58},[48,175,176],{"class":62},"();\n",[48,178,179,182,184,187],{"class":50,"line":102},[48,180,181],{"class":62},"console.",[48,183,83],{"class":58},[48,185,186],{"class":62},"(name); ",[48,188,189],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F name is not defined;\n",[17,191,192,193,196],{},"Because each function has its own scope and its own ",[45,194,195],{},"this",", every time you run a function you're running it in a different execution context.",[17,198,199,200,203,204,207],{},"This idea also applies to Node.js and the browser. When they run, both create a \"global execution context\" too — that's ",[45,201,202],{},"window"," in the browser and ",[45,205,206],{},"global"," in Node.js.",[12,209,211],{"id":210},"the-call-stack","The Call Stack",[17,213,214],{},[27,215],{"alt":216,"src":217},"Call stack","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-02%2020.55.53.png",[17,219,220],{},"The call stack is built on top of the execution context idea. Let's start with this bit of code:",[38,222,224],{"className":40,"code":223,"language":42,"meta":43,"style":43},"function a() {\n  b();\n}\n\nfunction b() {\n  c();\n}\n\nfunction c() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}\n\na();\n",[45,225,226,235,242,246,250,259,266,270,275,285,299,304,309],{"__ignoreMap":43},[48,227,228,230,233],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,229,55],{"class":54},[48,231,232],{"class":58}," a",[48,234,63],{"class":62},[48,236,237,240],{"class":50,"line":66},[48,238,239],{"class":58},"  b",[48,241,176],{"class":62},[48,243,244],{"class":50,"line":77},[48,245,105],{"class":62},[48,247,248],{"class":50,"line":96},[48,249,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[48,251,252,254,257],{"class":50,"line":102},[48,253,55],{"class":54},[48,255,256],{"class":58}," b",[48,258,63],{"class":62},[48,260,261,264],{"class":50,"line":108},[48,262,263],{"class":58},"  c",[48,265,176],{"class":62},[48,267,268],{"class":50,"line":115},[48,269,105],{"class":62},[48,271,273],{"class":50,"line":272},8,[48,274,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[48,276,278,280,283],{"class":50,"line":277},9,[48,279,55],{"class":54},[48,281,282],{"class":58}," c",[48,284,63],{"class":62},[48,286,288,291,293,295,297],{"class":50,"line":287},10,[48,289,290],{"class":62},"  console.",[48,292,83],{"class":58},[48,294,86],{"class":62},[48,296,90],{"class":89},[48,298,93],{"class":62},[48,300,302],{"class":50,"line":301},11,[48,303,105],{"class":62},[48,305,307],{"class":50,"line":306},12,[48,308,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[48,310,312,315],{"class":50,"line":311},13,[48,313,314],{"class":58},"a",[48,316,176],{"class":62},[17,318,319,320,323,324,327,328,330,331,333,334,337,338,340],{},"When JavaScript runs this, it actually stacks things up layer by layer, and each layer runs inside a specific execution context. In the code above, ",[45,321,322],{},"b()"," is called from inside ",[45,325,326],{},"a()",", so ",[45,329,322],{}," only lives as long as ",[45,332,326],{},". Same goes for ",[45,335,336],{},"c()"," inside ",[45,339,322],{},".",[17,342,343],{},"Like I said, JavaScript stacks these up layer by layer when it runs — but here's the key thing to remember: the very bottom layer is always the global execution context. So if you picture the whole call stack for these functions, it looks like this:",[17,345,346],{},[27,347],{"alt":348,"src":349},"How the call stack works","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E5%9F%B7%E8%A1%8C%E5%A0%86%E7%96%8A.gif",[17,351,352,353,357,358,361,362,364],{},"So your call stack has nothing to do with how you ",[354,355,356],"em",{},"declare"," your functions — it's all about how you ",[354,359,360],{},"call"," them. And even though the stack builds up layer by layer, functions don't get released starting from ",[45,363,326],{},". They get released starting from the last one in:",[17,366,367],{},[27,368],{"alt":369,"src":370},"Releasing functions","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E9%87%8B%E6%94%BE%E5%9F%B7%E8%A1%8C%E5%A0%86%E7%96%8A.gif",[17,372,373],{},"We can also use the browser to watch the call stack release in real time — just keep your eye on the Call Stack panel:",[17,375,376],{},[27,377],{"alt":378,"src":379},"Call stack release order","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002Fur3mq-se3kt.gif",[17,381,382],{},[383,384,385],"del",{},"I definitely didn't pull some rewind-video trick here",[17,387,388],{},"So you can see the call stack pushes and pops in this order:",[17,390,391,392,394,395,394,397,399,400,402,403,402,405],{},"Push: ",[45,393,326],{}," -> ",[45,396,322],{},[45,398,336],{},"\nPop: ",[45,401,326],{}," \u003C- ",[45,404,322],{},[45,406,336],{},[12,408,410],{"id":409},"references","References",[412,413,414],"ul",{},[415,416,417],"li",{},[314,418,422],{"href":419,"rel":420},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[421],"nofollow","Hexschool - JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[424,425,426],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font